			<h3 class="first"><a href="#p1011">Re: Collision Component / Trigger Component</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=1011&amp;sid=a3a20d64bd71fc50b16ad3e347cb0cc4#p1011"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Mensagem" title="Mensagem" /></a>por <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=97&amp;sid=a3a20d64bd71fc50b16ad3e347cb0cc4" style="color: #000066;" class="username-coloured">thelinuxlich</a></strong> &raquo; 21 Jun 2011, 10:38 </p>

			

			<div class="content">Systems/Behaviors/Aspects are not tied only to Components, they can communicate with each other(but beware of strong coupling), they can use some OOP spice where needed and they can process external stuff to act as a bridge between Components and specialized engines(like a RenderingSystem)<br /><br />If the entities need a &quot;mailbox&quot; with a list of messages, I see no problem implementing this as a Component with a Dictionary like you said, but avoid trying to go a hybrid route mixing events and clock-driven logic or you can lose all the benefits of a Entity System and just add bloat to the game. If all Components can have a message list, this can make gamestate saving/loading and networking much more complex.<br /><br />Currently, gametick logic goes like this:<br /><br />1 - World refreshes all entities(thus updating systems arrays of entities they are interested, triggering Added() and Removed() where implemented), removes all entities which were <br />flagged as removed on the previous gametick, removes all group null references<br />2 - Systems call Begin(), then CheckProcessing(), then Process(), then End()(everything is overridable)<br /><br />I'm not aware of the Ploobs way of sending/receiving messages, but I can see pub/sub or event driven paradigm converted into clock-driven, each system/aspect is unique, thus it would be strange to send the exact same message twice and process it twice on the same gametick.</div>

			

		</div>

		
